# ─────────────────────────────────────────────
#  .cursorrules — HR App Backend
#  Java 17 + Spring Boot 3 + MySQL
# ─────────────────────────────────────────────

## Project overview
This is a multi-tenant HR management SaaS application.
Backend: Java 17, Spring Boot 3.5.15, Spring Security, Spring Data JPA, MySQL 8.
Auth: JWT token-based authentication.
Architecture: REST API consumed by a React Native mobile app.

## Roles
- SUPERADMIN: platform owner (us), no company_id
- ADMIN: company CEO/owner, full access within their company
- HR: HR manager, day-to-day HR ops within their company
- EMPLOYEE: regular staff, own data only

## Architecture rules — follow strictly

### Package structure
com.hrapp/
  config/         → SecurityConfig, JwtConfig, SwaggerConfig
  controller/     → REST controllers only, no business logic
  service/        → all business logic lives here
  repository/     → JPA repositories, custom queries here
  entity/         → JPA entity classes, one per DB table
  dto/
    request/      → incoming request body classes
    response/     → outgoing response body classes
  security/       → JwtUtil, JwtFilter, CustomUserDetailsService
  exception/      → GlobalExceptionHandler, custom exceptions
  enums/          → SalaryType, AttendanceStatus, AttendanceSource, PunchType, LeaveRequestStatus, AdvanceStatus, PaymentStatus

### Entity rules
- Always annotate with @Entity, @Table(name = "table_name")
- Always use @Id, @GeneratedValue(strategy = GenerationType.IDENTITY)
- Use @Column(name = "column_name", nullable = false) explicitly
- Use Lombok: @Getter @Setter @NoArgsConstructor @AllArgsConstructor @Builder
- Never use @Data on entities (causes issues with JPA proxies)
- Relationships: use @ManyToOne @JoinColumn for FK columns
- All timestamps: use LocalDateTime, annotate with @CreationTimestamp or @UpdateTimestamp
- Never expose entity directly in controller — always map to DTO

### DTO rules
- Request DTOs: suffix with Request (e.g. LoginRequest, CreateUserRequest)
- Response DTOs: suffix with Response (e.g. LoginResponse, UserResponse)
- Use @Valid on controller method params
- Use bean validation annotations: @NotBlank @NotNull @Size @Email @Pattern
- Use Lombok: @Getter @Setter @NoArgsConstructor @AllArgsConstructor @Builder

### Controller rules
- Annotate with @RestController @RequestMapping("/endpoint")
- Inject service via constructor injection (not @Autowired field injection)
- Always return ResponseEntity<ApiResponse<?>>
- Keep controllers thin — only call service methods
- Use @Valid on @RequestBody params
- Group endpoints by module: AuthController, UserController, AttendanceController, LeaveController, PayrollController

### Service rules
- Annotate with @Service
- Inject repositories via constructor injection
- All business logic lives here
- Throw custom exceptions (ResourceNotFoundException, UnauthorizedException, etc.)
- Use @Transactional on methods that write to DB

### Repository rules
- Extend JpaRepository<Entity, Long>
- Custom queries: use @Query with JPQL (not native SQL) unless complex
- Name methods clearly: findByMobileAndStatus, findByCompanyIdAndMonth etc.

### Security rules
- Every API must check company_id matches logged-in user's company_id
- SUPERADMIN can access any company
- EMPLOYEE can only access their own data
- Extract logged-in user from SecurityContext using helper method
- Never trust company_id from request body — always use the logged-in user's company_id

### Standard API response wrapper
Every API returns this structure:
{
  "success": true/false,
  "message": "human readable message",
  "data": { ... } or null,
  "errors": null or { ... }
}
Use ApiResponse<T> generic wrapper class for this.

### Exception handling
- GlobalExceptionHandler with @RestControllerAdvice
- Custom exceptions: ResourceNotFoundException (404), UnauthorizedException (403), BadRequestException (400), ConflictException (409)
- Always return ApiResponse with success: false on errors

### Multi-tenancy rule
Every service method that fetches company data must filter by company_id.
Never return data from another company. SUPERADMIN bypasses this filter.

## Code style
- Use constructor injection always, never @Autowired on fields
- No System.out.println — use @Slf4j (Lombok) and log.info / log.error
- Keep methods small and focused — one method, one job
- Write comments only on complex business logic, not obvious code
- Use Optional properly — don't call .get() without checking isPresent()
- Meaningful variable names — no single letters except loop counters